<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="177" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="177">
Species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus traili" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="traili">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus traili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group are difficult to discern and constitute a widespread species complex (see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" author="Baca, SM" journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics and Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" pagination="1 - 4" refId="B2" refString="Baca, SM, Short, AEZ, 2020. Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity. Insect Systematics and Diversity 4 (6): 1 - 4, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" title="Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" volume="4" year="2020">Baca and Short 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Personal observations coupled with the phylogenetic reconstructions of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" author="Baca, SM" journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics and Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" pagination="1 - 4" refId="B2" refString="Baca, SM, Short, AEZ, 2020. Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity. Insect Systematics and Diversity 4 (6): 1 - 4, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" title="Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" volume="4" year="2020">Baca and Short (2020)</bibRefCitation>
show that the diagnostic power of the dorsal punctation (see 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" author="Young, FN" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" pagination="285 - 293" refId="B18" refString="Young, FN, 1978. The New World species of the water-beetle genus Notomicrus (Noteridae). Systematic Entomology 3 (3): 285 - 293, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" title="The New World species of the water-beetle genus Notomicrus (Noteridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" volume="3" year="1978">Young 1978</bibRefCitation>
) is unreliable, with multiple clades within the complex sharing similar patterns of punctation; for example, the pattern of punctation attributed to 
<taxonomicName family="Noteridae" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. gracilipes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" rank="species" species="gracilipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">N. gracilipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" author="Young, FN" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" pagination="285 - 293" refId="B18" refString="Young, FN, 1978. The New World species of the water-beetle genus Notomicrus (Noteridae). Systematic Entomology 3 (3): 285 - 293, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" title="The New World species of the water-beetle genus Notomicrus (Noteridae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1365-3113.1978.tb00121.x" volume="3" year="1978">Young (1978)</bibRefCitation>
arises in multiple places within the complex. The group will require careful taxonomic investigation. The members of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus traili" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="traili">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus traili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group can be difficult to distinguish from those of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus meizon" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meizon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus meizon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, but mature members lack a pigmented triangular area at the base of the elytra and most males of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus traili" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="traili">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus traili</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group have similarly-shaped median lobes of the aedeagus, distinct from the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus meizon" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meizon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus meizon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. See notes in remarks of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus meizon" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="meizon">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus meizon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="177" type="5. insertae sedis species">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="177">
5. 
<taxonomicName genus="Insertae" lsidName="Insertae sedis" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" rank="species" species="sedis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Insertae sedis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="177">
These species present characters combinations not found in other species groups. Both by presented character combination and even general 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">gestalt</emphasis>
, these are difficult to place with certainty. Molecular sequence data were unavailable for these species in the phylogenetic reconstruction of 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" author="Baca, SM" journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics and Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" pagination="1 - 4" refId="B2" refString="Baca, SM, Short, AEZ, 2020. Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity. Insect Systematics and Diversity 4 (6): 1 - 4, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" title="Molecular phylogeny of the notomicrine water beetles (Coleoptera: Noteridae) reveals signatures of Gondwanan vicariance and ecological plasticity." url="https://doi.org/10.1093/isd/ixaa015" volume="4" year="2020">Baca and Short (2020)</bibRefCitation>
. In particular, the species listed here both exhibit body shape, color, microsculpture and sparse punctation that would place them in the 
<taxonomicName family="Noteridae" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. nanulus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" rank="species" species="nanulus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">N. nanulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group. However, in comparison with the 
<taxonomicName family="Noteridae" genus="N." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="N. tenellus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" rank="species" species="tenellus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">N. tenellus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species group, the sister to all New World taxa, several of these characters appear plesiomorphic in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1882" class="Insecta" family="Noteridae" genus="Notomicrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Notomicrus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="177" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="177">Notomicrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, making it difficult to discern their likely relatives from morphology alone.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
